[The WHO report above indicates that there are 8 human cases (6 confirmed) and 3 deaths. Both reports state that cases are geographically widespread and have occurred in 6 regions. No mention is made of vaccination of domestic animals in either report.

As noted earlier, although people can become infected through contact with sick animals or their tissues and secretions, RVF virus can also be transmitted by mosquitoes. An earlier report indicated that this year's [2018's] heavy rainfall has resulted in widespread flooding in low-lying grasslands. Flooding and standing water have enabled a higher number of mosquito eggs than usual to hatch and thus has increased the potential for RVF to spread among people and animals.

The RVF virus is endemic in the Eastern Africa region and has caused repeated outbreaks in the past. It affects primarily ruminant livestock, such as cattle, sheep, goats, and camels, and also wildlife such as buffalos. In these animals, it causes abortions and deaths, resulting in significant economic loss.

The RVF virus can also affect humans. Most infections are mild, but some people fall severely ill and even die, with symptoms such as fever, weakness, and bleeding from the gums and mouth. The majority of human infections result from direct or indirect contact with the blood, body fluids, or tissues of infected animals. This can happen during slaughtering or butchering, while assisting with animal births or treating the animals, and from contact with disposed carcasses or fetuses. - Mod.TY

